2026-04-16 12:37:18 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control module output cable positive terminal clamp/crimp (at connector)'] hypothesis_explanation='All continuity and low-resistance measurements were performed with no appreciable current (unloaded), and showed good connection throughout the positive path from the relay to the load cable. However, under load, although there is 12V at the relay output, the voltage at the control module output cable (+) drops to near 0V and no current is delivered to the load. This strongly suggests there is a faulty joint—most likely a fractured crimp, cold solder, or terminal clamp—at or very near the point where the output cable attaches to its terminal/connector, which only fails under load due to marginal contact. This matches classic symptoms of a high-resistance (intermittent/open) connection that tests fine at low currents but blocks current under load. Previous repairs missed this very localized and load-dependent fault.'
